==English==

{{rank|receive|tried|certainly|554|big|road|husband|blockquote}}

===Etymology===
From northern {{etyl|enm|en}} dialect {{term|big|lang=enm}}, {{term|bigge||powerful, strong|lang=enm}}, of uncertain origin, possibly from a dialect of {{etyl|non|en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/bɪɡ/}}
* {{audio|en-us-big.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|ɪɡ}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|bigg|er}}

# Of a great [[size]]; [[large]]; the weakest sense of great size.
#: ''Elephants are '''big''' animals, and they eat a lot.''
# Of an industry or other field: Thought to have undue influence.
#: ''There were concerns about the ethics of '''big''' science.''
# [[popular|Popular]].
#: ''That style is very '''big''' right now in Europe, especially among teenagers.''
# {{informal}} [[Adult]].
#: ''Kids should get help from '''big''' people if they want to use the kitchen.''
# {{informal}} [[fat|Fat]].
#: ''Gosh, she is big!''
# {{informal}} [[important|Important]] or [[significant]].
#: ''What's so '''big''' about that?  I do it all the time.''
# {{informal}} (''construed with'' on) [[enthusiastic|Enthusiastic]] (about).
#: ''I'm not '''big''' on the idea, but if you want to go ahead with it, I won't stop you.''

